04845nam a22007455i 9780823296446DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20211992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232964467 a10.1515/97808232964462doi  a(DE-B1597)575305  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041202bisacsh00aRe: Joyce 'n Beckett /ced. by Phyllis Carey, Ed Jewinski. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (199 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between James Joyce and Samuel Beckett has long been of interest to literary critics and readers alike and Re: Joyce 'n Beckett explores that relationship more fully that any other single work of the current scholarship. This volume provides the reader with an overview of the main trends and dilemmas that have dominated discussions on the complex Joyce/Beckett relationship, and pulls together previously scattered materials into a cohesive whole. It also contains an extensive bibliography of particular interest to scholars who will find this composite of sources priceless. The main section offers eleven engaging new essays written from many points of view on a variety of topics including, the impact of biographies written on both Joyce and Beckett, the handling of Irish materials in the short story form, the use of allusion as well as larger narrative structures, the portrayal of the concept of the artist, and the way in which each author deals with the problem of "authority" in their writings. An original one-act play by Denis Regan is also included; the play premiered in April 1990 at the Milwaukee Irishfest. This work does much to challenge previous misconceptions about the Joyce/Beckett relationship. Re: Joyce 'n Beckett is a rich, lively work that brings the relationship of these two, crucially important literary figures of the twentieth century together in one definitive volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAcheson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrienza, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarey, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarey, Phyllis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohen, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnor, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Melvin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Michael Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, John P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJewinski, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJewinski, Ed, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLoxterman, Alan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRegan, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074329640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329644640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296446423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296446/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  a